on><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Gallbladder adenomyoma mimicking gallbladder cancer in a 53-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows a focal mass (arrow) in the fundus that is hypointense with areas of high signal intensity from dilated Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows that the mass (arrow) has a focus of higher signal intensity. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows that the mass (arrow) has fairly homogeneous enhancement, from hypervascular focal fundal adenomyomatosis mimicking gallbladder cancer. <b>(d)</b> Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the characteristic outpouchings from dilated Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (arrow), which distinguish the lesion from cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder adenomyoma mimicking gallbladder cancer in a 53-year-old woman. (a) Axial T2-weighted image shows a focal mass (arrow) in the fundus that is hypointense with areas of high signal intensity from dilated Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses. (b) Axial fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows that the mass (arrow) has a focus of higher signal intensity. (c) Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows that the mass (arrow) has fairly homogeneous enhancement, from hypervascular focal fundal adenomyomatosis mimicking gallbladder cancer. (d) Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the characteristic outpouchings from dilated Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (arrow), which distinguish the lesion from cancer."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig11d.jpeg" height="1193" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Gallbladder adenomyoma mimicking gallbladder cancer in a 53-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows a focal mass (arrow) in the fundus that is hypointense with areas of high signal intensity from dilated Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows that the mass (arrow) has a focus of higher signal intensity. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted image shows that the mass (arrow) has fairly homogeneous enhancement, from hypervascular focal fundal adenomyomatosis mimicking gallbladder cancer. <b>(d)</b> Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the characteristic outpouchings from dilated Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (arrow), which distinguish the lesion from cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Adenomyomatosis in a 71-year-old woman. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows apparent gallbladder wall thickening (arrow). (b) Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the “pearl necklace” sign (arrows), which refers to the characteristically curvilinear arrangement of multiple round hyperintense outpouchings."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig12a.jpeg" height="1194" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Adenomyomatosis in a 71-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows apparent gallbladder wall thickening (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the “pearl necklace” sign (arrows), which refers to the characteristically curvilinear arrangement of multiple round hyperintense outpouchings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Adenomyomatosis in a 71-year-old woman. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows apparent gallbladder wall thickening (arrow). (b) Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the “pearl necklace” sign (arrows), which refers to the characteristically curvilinear arrangement of multiple round hyperintense outpouchings."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig12b.jpeg" height="1194" width="1673" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Adenomyomatosis in a 71-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows apparent gallbladder wall thickening (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows the “pearl necklace” sign (arrows), which refers to the characteristically curvilinear arrangement of multiple round hyperintense outpouchings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder metastasis in a 57-year-old man with a history of renal cell carcinoma. He had undergone left nephrectomy. (a) Axial T1-weighted image shows an isointense small intraluminal gallbladder mass (arrow). (b) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows marked enhancement of the mass (arrow). The mass showed growth compared with its size on images 8 months earlier (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig13a.jpeg" height="1194" width="1672" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Gallbladder metastasis in a 57-year-old man with a history of renal cell carcinoma. He had undergone left nephrectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows an isointense small intraluminal gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows marked enhancement of the mass (arrow). The mass showed growth compared with its size on images 8 months earlier (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder metastasis in a 57-year-old man with a history of renal cell carcinoma. He had undergone left nephrectomy. (a) Axial T1-weighted image shows an isointense small intraluminal gallbladder mass (arrow). (b) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows marked enhancement of the mass (arrow). The mass showed growth compared with its size on images 8 months earlier (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig13b.jpeg" height="1194" width="1678" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Gallbladder metastasis in a 57-year-old man with a history of renal cell carcinoma. He had undergone left nephrectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows an isointense small intraluminal gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows marked enhancement of the mass (arrow). The mass showed growth compared with its size on images 8 months earlier (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. (b) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). (c) Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. (d) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. (e) Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig14a.jpeg" height="1233" width="1025" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. <b>(d)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. <b>(e)</b> Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. (b) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). (c) Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. (d) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. (e) Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig14b.jpeg" height="1233" width="1025" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. <b>(d)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. <b>(e)</b> Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. (b) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). (c) Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. (d) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. (e) Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig14c.jpeg" height="1246" width="1032" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. <b>(d)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. <b>(e)</b> Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. (b) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). (c) Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. (d) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. (e) Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig14d.jpeg" height="1246" width="1037" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. <b>(d)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. <b>(e)</b> Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14e" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. (b) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). (c) Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. (d) Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. (e) Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig14e.jpeg" height="1246" width="1031" aria-labelledby="fig14e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14e</span>. Gallbladder cancer in a 74-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image does not show a gallbladder mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted image does not show the gallbladder mass. <b>(d)</b> Axial portal venous phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows the enhancing gallbladder mass (arrow) without liver invasion. <b>(e)</b> Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted image shows a low-signal-intensity mass (arrow) in the gallbladder without liver invasion. At pathologic analysis, no tumor extension into the liver was found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig14e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. (a, b) Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted (a) and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted (b) images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. (c) Axial diffusion-weighted image (b = 500 sec/mm2) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. (d) Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig15a.jpeg" height="1194" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. <b>(c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted image (<i>b</i> = 500 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. <b>(d)</b> Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. (a, b) Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted (a) and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted (b) images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. (c) Axial diffusion-weighted image (b = 500 sec/mm2) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. (d) Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig15b.jpeg" height="1194" width="1673" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. <b>(c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted image (<i>b</i> = 500 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. <b>(d)</b> Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. (a, b) Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted (a) and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted (b) images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. (c) Axial diffusion-weighted image (b = 500 sec/mm2) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. (d) Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig15c.jpeg" height="1195" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. <b>(c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted image (<i>b</i> = 500 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. <b>(d)</b> Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. (a, b) Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted (a) and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted (b) images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. (c) Axial diffusion-weighted image (b = 500 sec/mm2) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. (d) Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig15d.jpeg" height="1195" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Gallbladder cancer in an 80-year-old woman with jaundice. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> images show a mass (arrows) invading the duodenal bulb with dilatation of the stomach. <b>(c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted image (<i>b</i> = 500 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows high signal intensity of the mass (arrow) from restricted diffusion. <b>(d)</b> Axial apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map shows that the mass is dark (arrows). The diagnosis was unresectable gallbladder tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Tumor recurrence in a 61-year-old man with a history of gallbladder cancer who had undergone cholecystectomy. (a) Axial T2-weighted image shows a hyperintense lesion in the gallbladder fossa (arrow). (b) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (arrow), compatible with local tumor recurrence."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig16a.jpeg" height="1193" width="1673" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Tumor recurrence in a 61-year-old man with a history of gallbladder cancer who had undergone cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows a hyperintense lesion in the gallbladder fossa (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (arrow), compatible with local tumor recurrence.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Tumor recurrence in a 61-year-old man with a history of gallbladder cancer who had undergone cholecystectomy. (a) Axial T2-weighted image shows a hyperintense lesion in the gallbladder fossa (arrow). (b) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (arrow), compatible with local tumor recurrence."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200087/asset/images/large/rg.2021200087.fig16b.jpeg" height="1193" width="1678" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Tumor recurrence in a 61-year-old man with a history of gallbladder cancer who had undergone cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows a hyperintense lesion in the gallbladder fossa (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (arrow), compatible with local tumor recurrence.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200087&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Levy AD, Murakata LA, Rohrmann CA Jr. Gallbladder carcinoma: radiologic-pathologic correlation. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2001;21(2):295–314; questionnaire, 549–555.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiographics.21.2.g01mr16295">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih